 {"id":"bd-trgk","title":"Actor core abstraction: ActorRef, ActorCell, ActorId","description":"# Actor Core Abstraction

## Goal

Implement the foundational actor types that all other actor functionality builds upon.

## Types to Implement

### ActorId
- Unique identifier for an actor within the runtime
- Must be deterministic in lab runtime (arena-based allocation like TaskId/RegionId)
- Includes generation counter for safe reuse after actor termination

### ActorRef<M>
- Typed handle for sending messages to an actor
- Generic over message type M for compile-time type safety
- Cheap to clone (Arc-based or index-based)
- Methods: send(), try_send(), is_alive()
- Must integrate with obligation tracking (send returns Permit)

### ActorCell
- Internal runtime state for an actor:
  - actor_id: ActorId
  - region: RegionId (owning region)
  - mailbox: Receiver<M> (bounded channel)
  - state: ActorState (Created, Running, Stopping, Stopped)
  - parent: Option<ActorId> (supervisor)
  - children: Vec<ActorId> (supervised children)
  - restart_count: u32 (for backoff)
  - created_at: Time

## Integration Points

- ActorId stored in RuntimeState arena (like TaskId)
- ActorCell linked to owning Region (region close terminates actor)
- ActorRef uses same two-phase send as channels (reserve→commit)

## Implementation Notes

- Start in src/actor/mod.rs (new module)
- Re-export core types from lib.rs
- Use existing id.rs patterns for ActorId
- ActorRef should be Send + Sync

## Testing

- Unit tests for ActorId generation/reuse
- ActorRef send/receive in lab runtime
- Verify actor termination when region closes

